comments.author: thomascooper2017

comments.text: I'm glad you like this Thomas. Unfortunately this shape is created using an extremely hacky method - essentially just placing a lot of short sections near to each other as you move around a circle (zoom in close and you'll see what I mean) and so it tends not to be able to create something you can actually 3d print. This should actually be made using a single surface (using functions and modules to make polygons, then assembling them into polyhedrons for each section of the shape, and joining them all together). At the time I wrote this I was not too comfortable with using some of OpenSCAD's more advanced capabilities , but bear with me and I'll have a look at making a more useful version over the next few days.

This will be a serie of files. First I printed the  NewlittlePotjeEnkelPotje.stl  which is the container.  Then I printed NewPotjeDekselmetGat2.stl  which is the top with the hole in its center.  
Then I printed potje toptest-cube.stl.   It is that big so it will fit on top of the top of the container.  The holes are for making the connection.  
At last I printed the claw.  It is tiny  and I had to clean it up a bit.

This was made in Autodesk 123d.  For simple geometric forms this program is very good.   My New little pot is  6.1 cm height and it took  around 3 hours  with my Ultimaker to print.  
The top of the container took about 1:30 hour to print.  It is a little difficult to get the top fitting into the container. But you have to take patience and twist it around a lot. Then it will work.   
The artistic top took about 1:30 hour to print. The height is 5 cm. the hole is for the connection.  The plug will follow.  
Now the tiny claw is printed I have al parts ready. The claw is 1 cm in diameter. It took 14 minutes to print. I had it filled 100% so that it is strong.  
Maybe you have to get some sandpaper for the claw to fit.  Or a file.  But it worked.  The connection is a little loose but it is my first connection made so  not bad at all.

This device was created to allow for student experiments to study fly ambulation (walking) in a controlled space.  There are 6 troughs and the flies move inside the tunnels created by the plastic body and affixed plexiglass top.  They always move upwards so this can be thought of as an upside down hour glass.  Students turn over the whole device for the next trial.  The plan is for students to record video of the experiment for analysis, and the plastic is thin enough to allow for backlighting if desired.

This was designed to fit on a 3D printer with a 200mm bed but can be scaled in the source file (SketchUp).  
Printed in PLA for accuracy and minimizing warping along with 2 shells and 25% in-fill.  No support is needed, but there is intentional support strands and cross pieces underneath the main body that should be removed after printing.  
For each device, one needs to print out 4 magnet holders, one body, and two bases (the STL already has two bases in it).  Further, we used 4 1/4"x1/4" cylinder neodymium magnets inside the body, and we glued 4 1/4"x1/8" cylinder neodymium magnets inside the magnet holders and the magnet holders to the plexiglass.  
The plexiglass was cut to approximately 90x134mm and is 2.3mm thick, Optix grade.

description.text: UPDATE: Check out the new improved version here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1421337 - it includes an option for free spinning wheels that attach to any Cubelet. These are magnetically attachable wheels for the Cubelets system from Modular Robotics, a construction system for quickly building robots. They are designed to attach to the "Rotate" Cubelet to give robots greater mobility. You will need to reprogram the Cubelets in opposing sides to turn counter-clockwise. It requires washers, and o-rings to use as the tires. The washers I used have an outer diameter of 1" and an inner diameter of 1/2". The dimensions are in the OpenSCAD file, so you can change them. You can probably get by with an OD 1mm smaller and/or an ID up 5mm larger. A larger ID will give a stronger piece, since it will allow the "pie slices" to overlap the hub more. Check McMaster Carr and see what they have... The o-rings I used for the medium wheel have an OD of 2 7/8" and an ID of 2 1/2". You can change this in the OpenSCAD file too. RC car tires would probably look cool. For assembly, print the wheel of your choice and the connector housing. You should use support material when printing the wheel in order to fill in the well for the connector. Fit the washer into the connector housing. Then press the connector housing into the wheel hub. Use glue if you want, but the friction fit is pretty good. The OpenSCAD file contains a bunch of utilities that can be used to make other Cubelets accessories. I am planning on making a pen holder, for example. IMPORTANT NOTE REGARDING MAGNETS: The pictures show a version of the connector with 1/8" magnets fitted. These provide a better connection, but are not recommended if you will use the wheels with small children, since the magnets could get loose and be swallowed. So I have uploaded the connector WITHOUT magnets, since this works fine and is safer. If you really want the magnets, you should be able to figure out how to get that version of the connector. ANOTHER NOTE ABOUT MAGNETS: Should you use the magnets, be aware that there is a correct polarity for installing them. They should be oriented such that they repel the magnets on a regular Cubelet. That way, when you bring them together, the magnets will repel each other, and instead seek out the washer, aligning the connector correctly. If the magnets are installed such that they attract the magnets on the Cubelet, then they will tend to stick magnet-to-magnet, and will require a twist and push to get them into the right orientation.

description.text:
A simplified replica of the Dark One Dagger from the ABC TV Series Once Upon A Time. This model was made with a 6" cubic build area in mind and should fit accordingly. Tolerances work very well, but I recommend cleaning out the sockets before attempting to dry fit anything together. Assembled model is approximately 19" in total length. Available Blade Variants:
Emma Swan
Blank
Killian Jones (coming soon)
Nimue (coming soon)
Zoso (coming soon) UPDATE: Per suggestion, full dagger file sets are available via zip files.

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Printrbot Simple Metal

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes: I did an infill of 20% to give it a bit more heft, though 10% infill would also be fine. There are a few supports made within the reverse-side pattern, but its easy enough to clean. I recommend using a heated bed to get the blade straight.

Finishing There will most likely be support material within the sockets. Clean them out well and everything will fit together fine. I was too eager to get the prop together on my first print and I ended up breaking the pommel tenon off inside the handle socket. Don't make my mistake! Clean your prints! I would recommend painting the completed prop to get a nice metallic sheen and blackened engraving details. Happy Printing!

things that go bump in the night
if you download please shoot me a like thanks ( ;

These are the specific plaques I built from my sliding plaque system (see the design it's remixed from) for my recycling sorting center.  There's a picture of the center included because, hey, why not?  (If anyone's interested, I can even share a SketchUp file of the center itself, as a carpentry product.  But you can't 3D-print that!)

See the source design for instructions, as well as for the frames into which these slide.  
In the images you can see these done as a two-color print.  All I did was slice it, then insert a pause command in between the last layer of the solid backing, and the first player of the letters.  During the pause, I move the head aside, change filament, and then resume.  When changing from a light color to black, I can start the print as soon as filament is flowing -- no need to work out the rest of the green first, the black will show clearly soon enough.  (Changing from black back to a light color in between plaques, however, requires feeding a ton of filament through.)

I tried to make the memory gun from gravity falls. The issue I ran into is every shot of this darn thing is slightly different so the ability to figure out any dimensions is sorta moot. This is most of the parts that should be 3d printed however their are parts that aren't really suited to 3d printing. Which can be bought at a hardware store or for some a specialty shop. There is a plate that slots into the back of the gun in case you don't want to put electronics inside. You will need:
-A flame tip lightbulb
-A lightbulb socket with an outer diameter of 38mm to fit in the barrel part.
-A red piece of clear plastic for the shield shown in the cartoon that goes at the end of the barrel, the shield is the template for this
-2 brass hinges for the tube and it's door
-1/8" rod for some of the pivots
-.05" rod for the trigger that will connect the spring to the body
-a small spring

This is my first attempt at a modification to my printer and I'm pretty pleased with it. I love printing with my Huxley - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5631 - but one of the frustrations is the major impact on print quality with even minor variation in the height of the nozzle when printing the first layer. I use spark plug feeler gauges to set the height to 0.2 mm for a 0.3 mm layer height but I found the method of adjusting the Z-endstop didn't give me the level of control I wanted.
So I replace the old bracket with a new longer one; I found an old 6 mm hex head bolt with a couple of nuts that fitted; I added a couple of parametric thumbwheels - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:13807; and finally, I designed a new bracket to fit on the side of the X-motor bracket.

title: Camera Mount for bare USB Webcam Board (v3)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Version three of my efforts to design a chassis and goose neck supporting a webcam for 3d printers. With version 3, I think I've got some standardized connections that should allow me to redesign parts in the future without needing to change everything. This design is made with a bare board camera in mind. Many of these cameras seem to have a standard mounting that will fit nicely inside this mount. Here is one at Amazon.Com that I am using on my own Rostock Max: http://www.amazon.com/180degree-Fisheye-1080p-Angle-Camera/dp/B00LQ854AG I am using my design for a ball and socket joint with a locking ring for the goose neck. These appear to be working well, but I may end up redesigning these at some point in the future to improve the grip further. If I do, I'll still use the threaded top ball to make it compatible with any other designs I make. Here is a link to this design, but I've included the parts in this build as well: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1393617 Use as many of the ball and socket joints as you like to make the proper length and flexibility for your goose neck. I have created three different types of camera chassis backs as well as two different types of camera chassis fronts. Choose one of each to suit your own purposes. For camera backs, my initial version is 15mm thick, which fits a board camera with enough room for wiring as long as you remove any connectors from the board camera and subsequently solder the USB wires directly to the board. Some people may not want to do that, so I also created one that is 20mm thick which would allow the camera board to fit without the need to remove the connector. Additionally, the thicker version allows a little extra room in case you find a need to stuff additional components inside. The third camera back may fit the Raspberry Pi's camera module. I don't have one myself to test, so this one is questionable. If it works for you, please tell me. This design requires four additional small screws to secure the Raspberry Pi camera module directly to the camera back, since the holes don't match up with the ones on the USB camera board. The Raspberry Pi camera module also uses a flat cable instead of a round one, but you may be able to curl up the cable and stuff it down the channel. YMMV. With the camera fronts, the first version only has an opening for the camera lens to stick out. The second version is a little thicker, but allows for the addition of an Adafruit Neopixel 12-LED ring. This ring can be controlled with a separate Arduino to illuminate the print bed, or for whatever signaling purposes you can dream up. In addition to the groove to mount the LED ring, there are holes for Neopixel wiring. Here is a link to the Neopixel RGB ring that I designed this for: https://www.adafruit.com/products/1643 There is also a new RGBW Neopixel ring that may also fit, and might put out more light in "full-on" mode. You can find it as well on the Adafruit website. There is also a thin cover that you can place over the ring for aesthetic reasons. It isn't necessary, but it might help protect the Neopixel ring which has exposed components. If you want to use it, just glue it in place with a little hot melt glue. Try not to get hot melt glue on the LEDs themselves. The front and back connect together using four standard #2 wood screws. For the "bare" front, you can use 1/2" wood screws, while the thicker "light ring" front requires 3/4" screws. With the "light ring" design, the wood screws also secure the ring. These can be found at your nearby hardware store, or on Amazon.Com: http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001387OQG
http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B001381E62 The camera back screws into the top of a ball and socket joint, both of which have been threaded with 14mm x 2mm ISO Metric Trapezoidal threads. I have found this thread type seems to print better than others, and the parts just fit together with little need for filing or scaling. The other end of the goose neck connects to the base mount, which has a mounting ball on top and a threaded portion on bottom. The base threads are 20mm x 2mm ISO Metric Trapezoidal threads, Print out a couple of the base washers and one of the base nuts and this will mount nicely in a hole that is about 7/8" in diameter As mentioned earlier, I may change this design slightly in the future, perhaps adding additional camera front pieces for different lighting ideas, and I may redesign the ball and socket joint at some time. However, I will strive to maintain compatibility with all other parts used.

Notes: I printed all the parts for this in PLA, using rafts for all parts except for the base nut and base washers. The ball and socket connectors and the retaining ring were multiplied in Cura, and printed 9 at a time on a raft, which seems to result in a better print quality than printing them one at a time. The camera front with light ring requires supports to print well, but you may find a better way to print it than I have.

After printing, you will probably want to check the ball joints for any significant imperfections.  A slightly rough finish is fine, and will actually work to provide additional grip.  However, if there are large imperfections you will probably want to file them to allow the ball to move cleanly within the socket.
Assembly should be fairly straightforward, but may require some soldering skills depending on parts used.

description.text:
These are frame components for a delta printer using 80/20 1010 (1") T-Slotted aluminum extrusions. The vertices are a derivative of mming1106's creation (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:208458).
  • The vertices are sized for 1x1" beams (25.4mm).
  • Access to the motor mounting bolts is provided through the face surface (requires a long Allen wrench).
  • Beam mounting is sized for 80/20's button head socket screws and T-Nuts.
  • There is cable access through the vertical beam mount (sized to ease cable routing).
  • And the top belt pulley is affixed with a nut in the first bulkhead so that it can be tightened without binding the bearings. ( I used 3 washers to shore up the gaps.)
    • To assemble, you will need:
  • 9 horizontal and 3 vertical 80/20 1010 T-Slotted aluminum beams
  • 45x 80/20 button head socket screws and T-Nuts
  • 6x 10mm x 4mm x 4mm flanged bearings for the belt pulleys
  • 3x M5 bolts (35 to 40mm long) and nuts with nylon inserts for tensioning the belts
  • 3x M4 bolts (25mm long), nuts with nylon inserts, and multiple washers for the belt pulleys
    • Sketchup files are included.

description.text:
A soap dish with plenty of ventilation for water to drain and air to flow, inspired by the art styling of Deus Ex Human Revolution. You may have never asked for this, but in bright yellow it'll be plenty easy to spot. 
"Soap Dish Feet.STL" is the "full" version with a concave top, and little feet to hold it off your surface its on. If you dont want it draining right on the counter, print "Soap dish pan.stl" for a pan with lips on 3 sides so it will drain towards the sink.  
"Soap dish easymode.stl" has the little feet, but no concave top so it will be easy to print upside down without support material, but is still compatible with the pan. 
"Soap dish flat.stl" is concave top, but without the feet; a flat bottom. It wont drain water well on a flat surface if thats what youre putting it on. 
If anyone has suggestions I.e. drain pan with 4 sides, thicker bottom on the drain pan (I did it in PETG so the thin bottom is plenty strong, maybe not in ABS/PLA?) feel free to comment and if it sounds reasonable I'll try to do some tweaks.
